SIMPLE: supernatural
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supernatural
<hw>Su`per*nat"u*ral</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Pref. <ets>super-</ets> + <ets>natural</ets>: cf. OF. <ets>supernaturel</ets>, F. <ets>surnaturel</ets>.]</ety> <def>Being beyond, or exceeding, the power or laws of nature; miraculous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Preternatural.</syn>  -- <usage><er>Supernatural</er>, <er>Preternatural</er>. <xex>Preternatural</xex> signifies <xex>beside</xex> nature, and <xex>supernatural</xex>, <xex>above</xex> or <xex>beyond</xex> nature. What is very greatly aside from the ordinary course of things is <xex>preternatural</xex>; what is above or beyond the established laws of the universe is <xex>supernatural</xex>. The dark day which terrified all Europe nearly a century ago was <xex>preternatural</xex>; the resurrection of the dead is <xex>supernatural</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧That form which the earth is under at present is <xex>preternatural</xex>, like a statue made and broken again.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>T. Burnet.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Cures wrought by medicines are natural operations; but the miraculous ones wrought by Christ and his apostles were <xex>supernatural</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Boyle.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That is <qex>supernatural</qex>, whether it be, that is either not in the chain of natural cause and effect, or which acts on the chain of cause and effect in nature, from without the chain.</q> <rj><qau>Bushnell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We must not view creation as <qex>supernatural</qex>, but we do look upon it as miraculous.</q> <rj><qau>McCosh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The supernatural</b></col>, <cd>whatever is above and beyond the scope, or the established course, of the laws of nature.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Nature and the <xex>supernatural</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>H. Bushnell.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supernaturalism</ent>⟦br⟧
